\begin_layout Section
Materials and Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Study Area
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Data used in this analysis were collected from 21 randomly selected riparian
 areas in the northern range of Yellowstone National Park in June and July
 of 2010.
 These 21 observational sites originated from a database of stream sections
 that were either historically known to have beaver or were hypothesized
 to be a potential habitat for beaver based on gradient and stream order
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "marshall2013stream"

\end_inset

).
 The sites were selected using a spatially balanced random sampling algorithm
 (RRQRR).
 Each observational site was measured 100m by river length and extended
 25m away from the river.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Data Collection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Seed Traps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Willow seeds were collected using seed traps made with an adhesive called
 Tree Tanglefoot
\begin_inset Formula $^{Â©}$
\end_inset

 on plywood boards which were staked into the ground using shelf brackets.
 Two seed traps (measuring 30 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 60 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

) were placed 25 m from the margin of the 100 m river length transect line
 within 5 m of the river bank.
 These seed traps capture the ambient seed rain for the entire site.
 A third trap (measuring 30 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

) was placed on an area within the transect determined optimal for seedling
 establishment.
 Willow seeds at each site were counted then removed from all traps each
 week during the willow seed production season.
 We will use the sum of the seeds counted from each site in our model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Willow Height
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every willow within each site was measured from the center of the root base
 to the highest branch in centimeters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Overview of Modeling Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We constructed a Bayesian, zero inflated Poisson model to account for process
 variance and observation error in our analysis of the effect of willow
 height on seed production.
 We estimated the marginal posterior distributions of parameters, specifically,
 the threshold height for willow seed production.
 A comprehensive representation of the model follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P(\boldsymbol{z},p,\boldsymbol{\beta}\big|\boldsymbol{y}) & \propto & P(\boldsymbol{y}\big|\boldsymbol{\lambda})^{\boldsymbol{z}}P(y=0)^{\boldsymbol{z}-1}P(\boldsymbol{z}\big|p)P(p,\boldsymbol{\beta})\label{eq:overview}\\
\boldsymbol{\lambda} & = & \boldsymbol{X}\boldsymbol{\beta}\label{eq:lamtocovars}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{z}$
\end_inset

 represents our prediction of the true state of willow seed count that we
 observed in vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{y}$
\end_inset

 where either 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $z>0$
\end_inset

.
 The true state is derived from a process model when 
\begin_inset Formula $y>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z>0$
\end_inset

.
 Otherwise when 
\begin_inset Formula $y=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 with probability 1.
 The process model is formed by a deterministic regression shown in equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lamtocovars"

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}$
\end_inset

 is a matrix of covariates multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\beta}$
\end_inset

 a vector of parameters.
 We estimate these parameters in a parameter model.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:overview"

\end_inset

 will serve as a guide to our methods section.
 First we will outline the models of the data, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\boldsymbol{y}\big|\boldsymbol{\lambda})^{\boldsymbol{z}}P(y=0)^{\boldsymbol{z}-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, we will describe models of the process 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\boldsymbol{z}\big|p)$
\end_inset

 that determines the true state of willow seed production.
 Next, we will explain our choice of the parameter models, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(p,\boldsymbol{\beta})$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, we will assemble the full model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This three sub-model structure allows us to represent uncertainty associated
 with data collection in the data model, account for the underlying mechanisms
 from which the data are drawn in the process model, and define prior distributi
ons of the parameters in the parameter model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Data Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We chose a zero-inflated Poisson regression model because some sites 
\begin_inset Formula $(i)$
\end_inset

 had no seeds.
 Thus, our data model is represented below:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
y_{i} & \sim & \begin{cases}
0 & ,\: x_{i}=0\\
\mathrm{Poisson}(\lambda_{i}) & ,\: x_{i}>0
\end{cases}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is our prediction of the true state and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the seed count data for site 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Process Model
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Process-Model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We seek to estimate a threshold height for willow seed recruitment, but
 we also recognize that the number of willows in a plot among other things
 should effect seed production.
 To estimate the effect of willow height and numbers of willow in the plot
 on seed recruitment, we created an indicator variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 to count the number of willows in each plot above a threshold height 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\tilde{h}\right)$
\end_inset

 with an interaction effect with total willow height 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ij}$
\end_inset

 for the site such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{i}=\sum_{i=1}^{J_{i}}1_{\{h_{ij}\geq\tilde{h}\}}h_{ij}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is an index for the individual willow.
 Then, to compute the intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda_{i})$
\end_inset

, we used the following regression model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{i}=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}\mathrm{log}(x_{i})
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 was only calculated when 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}>0$
\end_inset

 because as stated in the previous section if 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 with probability 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Parameter Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are three parameters in this model, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{h},\beta_{0},$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Previous evidence suggests that the threshold height for willow seed recruitmen
t is 200 cm (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "kay1991reduction"

\end_inset

), so we assigned an informative prior to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{h}$
\end_inset

 by moment matching a gamma distribution with mean = 200 and variance =
 50.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{h}\sim\mathrm{gamma}(4,.02)
\]

\end_inset

We gave the coefficients in our regression model vague priors with mean
 = 0 and variance = 50.
 We assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

 were independently and identically distributed.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{\beta}\sim N(\boldsymbol{\mu_{\beta}},\sigma^{2}I)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Posterior
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The full posterior and joint distributions are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline}
\left[\boldsymbol{\beta},\tilde{h}\biggm\vert y_{i}\right]\propto\underset{i}{\prod}\left(1_{\{y_{i}=0\}}^{1_{\{x_{i}=0\}}}\mathrm{Poisson}\left(y_{i}\biggm\vert\lambda_{i}\right)^{1_{\{x_{i}>0\}}}\right)\\
\times\mathrm{Multivariate\: Normal}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}\biggm\vert0,50\right)\mathrm{Gamma}\left(\tilde{h}\biggm\vert2,0.04\right)
\end{multline}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Implementation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Marginal posterior distributions of states, parameters, and model predictions
 were estimated using Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods in the R computing
 environment (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "rdevelopment2011team"

\end_inset

).
 Parameters were estimated using a random walk metropolis-hastings algorithm
 with normal proposal distributions.
 Three chains were chosen for each estimated quantity.
 Initial values of chains were each chosen to vary 20% in either direction
 relative to posterior distributions (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "brooks1998general"

\end_inset

).
 Convergence was assured by inspection of trace plots and by the diagnostics
 of Gelman and Rubin (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "gelman1992inference"

\end_inset

).
 All code for this model can be found in the supplementary materials.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we describe the results of our MCMC output.
 We accumulated 100,000 samples from each chain and discarded 20,000 iterations
 as the burn-in to ensure convergence of parameter chains.
 In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:The-marginal-posterior"

\end_inset

, we show the marginal posterior distributions of the model parameters,
 and in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:The-means-and"

\end_inset

 we report the means and 95% credible intervals of each parameter.
 The parameters converged after 100,000 iterations of the MCMC Sampler as
 indicated by the Gelman Diagnostics of 1.00 for all parameters with a 20,000
 iteration burn-in.
\end_layout

